\section{Nodeless High-T_\{c\} Superconductivity in the Highly Overdoped CuO_\{2\} Monolayer}
 Kun Jiang, Xianxin Wu, Jiangping Hu, and Ziqiang WangPhys. Rev. Lett. 121, 227002 - Published 29 November 2018

DOI: 10.1103/PhysRevLett.121.227002

\section*{Nodeless high- $\mathrm{T}_{c}$ superconductivity in highly-overdoped monolayer $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ }
(Dated: November 5, 2018)

\begin{abstract}
We study the electronic structure and superconductivity in $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer grown recently on $d$-wave cuprate superconductor $\mathrm{Bi}_{2} \mathrm{Sr}_{2} \mathrm{CaCu}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{8+\delta}$. Density functional theory calculations indicate significant charge transfer across the interface such that the $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer is heavily overdoped into the hole-rich regime yet inaccessible in bulk cuprates. We show that both the Cu $d_{x^{2}-y^{2}}$ and $d_{3 z^{2}-r^{2}}$ orbitals become important and the Fermi surface contains one electron and one hole pocket associated with the two orbitals respectively. Constructing a minimal correlated two-orbital model for the $e_{g}$ complex, we show that the spin-orbital exchange interactions produce a nodeless superconductor with extended $s$-wave pairing symmetry and a pairing energy gap comparable to the bulk $d$-wave gap, in agreement with recent experiments. The findings point to a direction of realizing new high- $T_{c}$ superconductors in ozone grown transition-metal-oxide monolayer heterostructures.
\end{abstract}

The commonly held belief of the high- $T_{c}$ cuprate superconducting (SC) state [1] is that the superconductivity originates from two-dimensional copper-oxide $\left(\mathrm{CuO}_{2}\right)$ planes with a nodal $d$-wave pairing symmetry $[2-4]$. In a recent attempt to directly probe the SC state in the copper-oxide plane, monolayer $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ on $\mathrm{Bi}_{2} \mathrm{Sr}_{2} \mathrm{CaCu}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{8+\delta}$ (Bi2212) has been grown successfully by the state-of-the-art ozone molecular beam epitaxy (MBE) [5]. In contrast to the widely observed V-shaped local density of states (LDOS) typical of a nodal $d$-wave pairing gap in bulk cuprates, scanning tunneling microscopy (STM) on the $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer reveals a robust U-shaped LDOS characteristic of a nodeless SC gap, which is further shown to be insensitive to nonmagnetic impurities [5]. Several theoretical scenarios have been proposed for this remarkable observation, largely based on the SC proximity effect but with the $d$-wave nodes avoided by different Fermi surfaces or coexisting magnetism in the monolayer [6-9]. Here, we propose a different scenario. We argue that the $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer has a new electronic structure due to interface charge transfer and exhibits an intrinsic nodeless, $s$-wave SC state. Thus while the monolayer may not be representative of the bulk $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ layers, it has potentially realized the direction of finding new and novel form of high- $\mathrm{T}_{c}$ superconductors in transition-metal-oxide heterostructures by interface charge transfer.

The main findings are summarized in the schematic phase diagram shown in Fig. 1. The left side of Fig. 1 has been realized by hole-doping the antiferromagnetic (AF) parent state in bulk cuprates, where the $3 d^{9} \mathrm{Cu}^{2+}$ has

