three $e_{g}$ electrons $\left(n_{e}=3\right)$ occupy the well-split $d_{x^{2}-y^{2}}$ $\left(d_{x^{2}}\right)$ and $d_{3 z^{2}-r^{2}}\left(d_{z^{2}}\right)$ orbitals due to Jahn-Teller distortion. The $d$-wave superconductor emerges under the SC dome with a maximum $T_{c}$ around an optimal doping concentration $x_{h} \sim 0.16$. Experiments show that the metallic state in bulk cuprates has a single band of the $d_{x^{2}}$ character [10] crossing the Fermi level. Note that heavy overdoping is difficult and the region with $x_{h}>0.3$ has not been accessible in bulk cuprates.

The right side of Fig. 1 is conjectured for the monolayer $\mathrm{CuO}_{2} / \mathrm{Bi} 2212$. Based on the experimental evidence suggesting that the monolayer crystalizes into $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}[5]$, significant charge transfer must occur between the $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer and the Bi2212 substrate in order to maintain charge neutrality. We will show that this is indeed supported by density functional theory (DFT) calculations and charge transfer correlations. Thus, the $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer is highly overdoped and reaches a regime yet inaccessible in bulk cuprates. As shown in Fig. 1, this hole-rich regime approaches $3 d^{8}\left(\mathrm{Cu}^{3+}\right)$ with $n_{e}=2$ in the two $e_{g}$ orbitals. We show that both $d_{x^{2}}$ and $d_{z^{2}}$ orbitals become active and the electronic structure requires a minimal two-band description with one electron FS enclosing $\Gamma$ and one hole FS around M (Fig. 1). Constructing a two-orbital Hubbard model and studying its SC properties using both weak and strong coupling approaches, we find that the hole-rich $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer is a multiband nodeless superconductor driven by both spinspin and spin-orbital entangled (super)exchange interactions. The pairing energy gaps are comparable in magnitude to the bulk $d$-wave gap and exhibit a sign-change on the two FS, analogous to Fe-based superconductors. The calculated STM conductance displays the U-shaped spectrum consistent with the experimental observations.

We first carry out a DFT calculation to simulate a $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer on Bi2212 using the Vienna ab initio simulation package (VASP) [11-15]. The details are given in the supplemental material (SM) [16]. As illustrated in Fig. 2(a), due to the missing apical oxygen in the unbalanced octahedron, the cation $\mathrm{Cu}$ attracts the bottom anion oxygen $\left(\mathrm{O}_{a}\right)$ and shortens the out-of-plane $\mathrm{Cu}-\mathrm{O}_{a}$ distance at the interface to $2.11 \AA$, after relaxation. This value is close to the in-plane $\mathrm{Cu}-\mathrm{O}$ bond length of $1.92 \AA$, which is much shorter than the $2.82 \AA \mathrm{Cu}-\mathrm{O}_{a}$ distance in the bulk. The point group symmetry $D_{4 h}$ also breaks down to $C_{4 v}$. There are two immediate consequences. (i) The $p_{z}$ orbital of the bottom $\mathrm{O}_{a}$ strongly hybridizes with the $\mathrm{Cu} d_{z^{2}}$ orbital. This leads to a $d_{z^{2}}$ like bonding orbital and transfers charges to the oxygen in the $\mathrm{BiO}$ layer. The excess charge transfer causes the $\mathrm{Cu}$ valence in the monolayer to approch $3 d^{8}\left(\mathrm{Cu}^{3+}\right)$ with two electrons occupying the $e_{g}$ orbitals. (ii) The crystal field splitting between the $d_{x^{2}}$ and $d_{z^{2}}$ orbitals is significantly reduced compared to in the bulk.

These phenomena show up in the calculated band structure shown in Fig. 2(b). The band highlighted by red markers contains the $d_{x^{2}}$ orbital mixed with the antisymmetric combination of the in-plane oxygen $p_{x}$ and $p_{y}$ orbitals [10]. We label this band as the $d_{x^{2}}$ band, which is heavily overdoped and electron-like near the zone center $\Gamma$. The green markers indicate the $d_{z^{2}}$ band of the $\mathrm{Cu} d_{z^{2}}$ orbital mixed with the anion oxygen $p_{z}$ orbital. It is holelike near the zone corner $M$, with its band top very close to the Fermi level. Thus, the monolayer $\mathrm{CuO}_{2} / \mathrm{Bi} 2212$ has a different electronic structure than the $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ layer in the bulk. Note that in the experiments [5], the $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer is MBE grown on Bi2212 substrates that are optimally hole doped by the excess oxygen dopants of which a substantial fraction resides near the $\mathrm{BiO}$ layers $[17,18]$. Their density is further increased in the top $\mathrm{BiO}$ layer in the ozone environment. As a result, additional charge transfer takes place via the oxygen dopants hole doping the $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ monolayer across the interface, which further stabilizes the $\mathrm{CuO}_{2}$ structure and pushes the chemical potential into the $d_{z^{2}}$ band. Consequently,\\
